Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide
chips (no need to peel). Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with
oil, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a
single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, combine the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml}, a drizzle
of @olive oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cut the @medium tomato{1} into 2cm chunks and add to the dressing. Set aside.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #large bowl{}, combine the garlic, @panko breadcrumbs{10%grams},
@salt{1/4%tsp} and @water{2%tbsp} for the breadcrumbs, then add the
@British beef mince{240%grams}.

Season with pepper and mix together with your hands.

Roll into even-sized balls, then shape into 1cm thick burgers, 1 per person.

> TIP: The burgers will shrink a little during cooking.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the burgers onto a large baking tray and bake on the middle shelf until
cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The burgers are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the chips have 5 mins left, in a #small saucepan{} heat
@creme fraiche{75%grams}, @chicken stock paste{10%grams} and
@water{50%ml} for the sauce.

Stir to combine and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium-low and
simmer until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once thickened, stir the @truffle zest{1%sachet} through the sauce. Season to
taste with salt and pepper, then remove from the heat.

> Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

When everything's ready, toss the @wild rocket{40%grams} through your balsamic
dressing.

Transfer the naked burgers to your plates and spoon over the truffle sauce.

Serve the salad and chips alongside.

Enjoy!